                     <interp inst="def1-260-18391125" type="surname" value="WHITCHELOW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-260-18391125" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM WHITCHELOW</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18391125-260-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18391125-260-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18391125-260-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18391125-cd-239" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18391125-260-offence-1 t18391125-cd-239"></join>3rd of November</rs>, 1 watch, value 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 2 waistcoats, value 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 pair of trowsers, value 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 handkerchief, value 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 4 sovereigns, and 5 half-sovereigns; the property of <persName id="t18391125-name-1283" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1283" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1283" type="surname" value="SPIERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1283" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18391125-260-offence-1 t18391125-name-1283"></join>William Spiers</persName>, in the dwelling-house of <persName id="t18391125-name-1284" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1284" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1284" type="surname" value="SPIERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1284" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18391125-260-offence-1 t18391125-name-1284"></join>William Spiers</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18391125-name-1285" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1285" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1285" type="surname" value="SPIERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1285" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD SPIERS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Southampton-street, in the parish of St. Giles, Camberwell, with my father, William Spiers—it is his house. I bought a silver watch of the prisoner about five weeks ago—I did not wear it at all, but gave it to my mother to take care of, in the course of the day, and did not see it again till it was at the pawnbroker's—I had a box with one sovereign in money in it in the house, and there were three sovereigns and five half-sovereigns in a small box in another room—my own box was in my own bed-room, and there was a half-sovereign lying on a table in the room—the other box was in my mother's care—on the 3rd of November I went up stairs to get some money, as my mother asked me to let her have a few shillings, and I found the box broken open—I had seen that box about a fortnight before—my watch was not in that box—I missed the three sovereigns and five half-sovereigns—I missed a sove<lb></lb>reign from my own box, which was also broken open—I had seen that box safe a fortnight before—I did not see my mother's small box a fortnight before, as I did not know where she kept it—the prisoner was in the habit of coming to my father's house for three or four months—he used to work with me, and came backwards and forwards to the house every other day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18391125-name-1286" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1286" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1286" type="surname" value="SPIERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1286" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH SPIERS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's mother. I received a watch from him, and put it into a drawer in a room next to my own—I did not see it again—I should know it again—my son gave me 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to take care of for him—I put them into a small box in my room—the box was found</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183911250177"></xptr>
               <p>opened by a false key, on the 3rd of November, and two strange keys were found in the room, one of which opened the box—my son's box was bro-ken open, and his purse and money was gone—I do not think I had seen that box before for some considerable time—the prisoner was in the habit of coming to our house, and knew where very thing was—I had been as<lb></lb>sisting him for some time when he was out of work, as his master dis<lb></lb>charged him at a moment's notice.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18391125-name-1287" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1287" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1287" type="surname" value="WHARTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1287" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WHARTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pawnbroker, and live in Crosby-row, Wal<lb></lb>worth. I produce a watch which was pawned at my shop on the 6th of November, by Mary Ann Broad.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18391125-name-1288" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1288" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1288" type="surname" value="BROAD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1288" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MART ANN BROAD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am sister to the prisoner. I pledged a watch which I received from my sister Elizabeth, who is in service at Mr. Wither's, at Camberwell—she is not here—I took it home, went to the prisoner, and questioned him about it, as I heard Mr. Spiers had lost a watch—I told him I had received a watch from Elisabeth, and was that the watch, and had he come by it dishonestly—he said no, he had not, the watch he sold Mrs. Spiers was a silver one, which he gate 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for, and this one he gave 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for—I begged him to tell the troth, that I might take it back to the owner, if it was hers—he said that it was not hers, that he paid 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for it at one time, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. at another, and 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. he borrowed of his sister, to pay the rest—the money which he got from the pawnbroker was laid out on his mother, who was lying on a sick-bed—it was pawned to assist her.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18391125-name-1289" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1289" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1289" type="surname" value="BARNETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1289" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES BARNETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I apprehended the prisoner on the 3rd of November, and told him I took him for a robbery at Mrs. Spiers', of a watch, money, and other articles—he said he knew nothing of the robbery—I took him to the station-house—I went to different pawn-brokers to find the property—I was present when the prisoner was examined before the Magistrate—(<hi rend="italic">looking at the examination</hi>)—this is Mr. Jeremy's, the Magistrate's signature—(<hi rend="italic">read</hi>)—"The prisoner says the watch pro<lb></lb>duced is not the watch sold to Spiers—it was a metal-cased watch—I know nothing about the money—I sold the watch now produced to my sister Elizabeth."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18391125-name-1290" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1290" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1290" type="surname" value="SPIERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18391125-name-1290" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD SPIERS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I am sure this is the watch I bought of him, I know it by a piece broken out of the edge of the case—I examined it when I bought it, sufficiently to identify it—I gave 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MRS. SPIERS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I know the watch to be the same.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. The watch the son bought of me had an old metal case to it, but it is silver inside. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. There is no other ease to it—he gave it to me, and was saving his money to change it away, to get a silver watch.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18391125-260-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
